tural Revolution. Through interviews with her own family members as well as their neighbors, classmates, and co-workers, Li weaves a complex social tapestry reflecting the lived experiences of ordinary people struggling to absorb and adapt to major historical change. These voices include workers, intellectuals, Communists, Nationalists, foreigners, compradors, wives, concubines, and children who all fought for a foothold and haven in this city, witnessing spectacles so full of farce and pathos they could only be whispered as secret histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aARCHITECTURExBuildingsxResidential. 0aChinesexDwellingsxChinaxShanghai. 0aChinesexDwellingszChinazShanghai. 0aDwellingsxChinaxShanghai. 0aDwellingszChinazShanghai. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCExCustoms & Traditions. 0aShanghai (China)xCivilization. 0aShanghai (China)xSocial life and customs. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/li--1671640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231538176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231538176.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK